+# Why does Liaison not use a relationship-strength score?
+
+## Context
+
+A contributor wants to surface relationships that may need attention and proposes a single numeric score based on message frequency, recency, profile completeness, or interaction volume.
+
+## Answer
+
+Do not implement a relationship-strength score. Keep relationship intent, recorded evidence, maintenance status, profile readiness, and review priority separate.
+
+The personal default is reason-only review. Show factual explanations such as an open commitment, an approaching birthday, or a cadence selected by the user. Weighted Review Priority is an optional queue-ordering policy and must expose its full component breakdown.
+
+## Why
+
+Communication volume does not establish affection, trust, consent, reciprocity, or importance. Strong relationships can be low-frequency. High-frequency communication can be unwanted or operational. A sparse profile can be an intentional privacy choice.
+
+## Verify
+
+- Search domain and UI code for `relationship strength`, `human value`, and unexplained numeric ranking.
+- Confirm personal workspaces default to reason-only mode.
+- Confirm `archived`, `do_not_contact`, `paused`, and `snoozed` suppress queue entries.
+- Confirm every surfaced person has one or more source-linked reasons.
+- Confirm employee ranking and employment-decision uses are prohibited.
+
+## Limits
+
+Review Priority can order a private queue when a user explicitly enables it. It remains a policy output, not a fact about the person or relationship, and must never be included in subject-facing exports by default.
