+# Liaison RM — Relationship Domain, Profile Topics, and Review Engine
+
+**Status:** Proposed normative product and domain contract
+**Version:** 0.4
+**Date:** 17 July 2026
+**Intended repository:** `Electric-Town/liaison-RM`
+
+## 1. Product position
+
+Liaison RM is a personal relationship manager with the operational discipline of a CRM, without treating friends, family, colleagues, or community relationships as sales leads.
+
+The product remembers factual context, preserves a chronological relationship record, helps a user decide where attention is useful, and explains every reminder or review suggestion. It supports individual users, executive assistants, families, community organizers, workplace teams, and people who need executive-function support for relationship maintenance.
+
+The system must never imply that communication frequency equals affection, trust, importance, or relationship quality. Some strong relationships are low-frequency. Some high-frequency relationships are unwanted or purely operational.
+
+Liaison therefore separates four concepts:
+
+1. **Relationship intent** — what the user wants this relationship to be and how much attention they intend to give it.
+2. **Relationship evidence** — interactions, shared activities, commitments, dates, notes, and connected resources.
+3. **Maintenance status** — whether the relationship is current relative to the user’s own cadence and rules.
+4. **Profile readiness** — whether the information needed for a particular purpose is known, current, and verified.
+
+A single universal “relationship score” is not the canonical model.
+
+---
+
+## 2. Coverage inherited from the reference products
+
+Liaison RM must cover the useful functions of both Meerkat CRM and CRM in Markdown.
+
+### Meerkat-equivalent coverage
+
+- create, edit, search, archive, and restore people;
+- circles and contact groups;
+- first-class relationships such as spouse, child, colleague, mentor, and friend;
+- CardDAV contact synchronization;
+- profile notes;
+- general notes and journaling;
+- activities involving one or multiple people;
+- a combined timeline;
+- reminders and recurring follow-ups;
+- birthdays and other important dates;
+- accessible light and dark themes;
+- localization-ready UI.
+
+### CRM-in-Markdown-equivalent coverage
+
+- one readable Markdown profile per person;
+- company records;
+- personal and business fields;
+- relationship type and relationship tier;
+- configurable contact cadence;
+- last contacted and next contact due;
+- contact reason and last meaningful topic;
+- communication log;
+- open tasks and commitments;
+- Today, Overdue, and This Week views;
+- monthly relationship review;
+- quick capture for people and interactions;
+- reusable outreach and follow-up templates;
+- archive state and archive reason;
+- Obsidian-compatible properties and views;
+- operation without Obsidian or any particular editor.
+
+Liaison extends these ideas with typed topic packs, organizations and memberships, connected resources, context-specific readiness, provenance, explainable review rules, and local-first collaboration boundaries.
+
+---
+
+## 3. Ubiquitous language
+
+| Term | Meaning |
+|---|---|
+| **Party** | An addressable entity in the relationship graph. A Party is a Person or Organization. It is not a generic database row shown to users. |
+| **Person** | A human profile with identity, contact channels, topic information, dates, and relationship links. |
+| **Organization** | A company, charity, school, club, government body, community, vendor, or other formal body. |
+| **Group** | A user-defined collection such as family, close friends, book club, event cohort, team, or people met at a conference. Groups can be static or query-based. |
+| **Household** | A specialized group representing people, pets, shared addresses, and household dates. |
+| **Membership** | A dated relationship between a Person and an Organization or Group, including role, title, department, location, and status. |
+| **Relationship** | A first-class edge between two entities. It has type, direction, state, dates, provenance, and optional user-authored assessment. |
+| **Topic Pack** | A reusable, typed set of fields and sections that can be enabled globally, by profile template, or for one entity. |
+| **Field State** | The epistemic state of a value: known, unknown, not applicable, declined, stale, unverified, or verified. |
+| **Interaction** | A meaningful contact event such as a call, message, meeting, introduction, gift, shared activity, or email. |
+| **Commitment** | A promise, requested action, or open loop involving one or more parties. |
+| **Resource** | A connected file, URL, calendar item, email thread, document, photo, location, or other reference. |
+| **Relationship Intent** | User-authored importance, desired cadence, boundaries, and desired future state. |
+| **Maintenance Status** | Explainable state derived from cadence, recency, commitments, important dates, and user rules. |
+| **Review Priority** | A configurable queue-ordering calculation. It is not a measure of human worth or objective relationship strength. |
+| **Profile Readiness** | Context-specific coverage of the fields required for a task, such as preparing a meeting or catering for an event. |
+
+---
+
+## 4. Domain model
+
+### 4.1 Person
+
+A Person contains stable identity and profile information. It does not directly own every note, interaction, file, or organization value; those are linked records to avoid a giant conflict-prone profile file.
+
+Core fields:
+
+- stable ID;
+- display name;
+- structured names, nickname, pronunciation, phonetic form, and pronouns;
+- photos and accessible text alternatives;
+- contact channels;
+- addresses and locations;
+- important dates;
+- tags and circles;
+- active profile templates/topic packs;
+- archive and contact-boundary state;
+- provenance summary;
+- derived, rebuildable review indicators.
+
+### 4.2 Organization
+
+Organization types include:
+
+- company;
+- nonprofit;
+- school or university;
+- government body;
+- community;
+- club;
+- religious organization;
+- vendor;
+- client;
+- household service provider;
+- informal organization.
+
+Organization fields can include domains, locations, industry, size range, departments, aliases, parent/child organizations, contacts, important dates, notes, files, URLs, and events.
+
+### 4.3 Group
+
+Groups are not forced into the Organization model.
+
+Examples:
+
+- family;
+- household;
+- close friends;
+- old school friends;
+- neighborhood;
+- conference contacts;
+- project team;
+- event attendees;
+- people to reconnect with;
+- gift list;
+- Dublin office;
+- VIP network.
+
+Group modes:
+
+- **static** — manually managed membership;
+- **dynamic** — membership produced by a saved query;
+- **snapshot** — a fixed cohort preserved for an event, review, or export;
+- **household** — shared addresses, pets, dates, and household relationships;
+- **team** — roles and collaborative records.
+
+### 4.4 Relationship
+
+Relationships are directional or reciprocal edges between:
+
+- Person and Person;
+- Person and Organization;
+- Person and Group;
+- Organization and Organization;
+- Organization and Group.
+
+Examples:
+
+- spouse / partner;
+- parent / child;
+- sibling;
+- friend;
+- neighbor;
+- mentor / mentee;
+- executive / assistant;
+- colleague;
+- manager / report;
+- client contact;
+- member of;
+- introduced by;
+- referred by;
+- works at;
+- volunteers with;
+- supplier to;
+- parent organization of.
+
+Relationship data:
+
+- type and reciprocal label;
+- direction;
+- start and end dates;
+- active, paused, distant, strained, ended, or archived state;
+- source and confidence;
+- shared contexts;
+- private notes stored separately;
+- manual relationship intent;
+- optional manual assessment dimensions;
+- follow-up policy.
+
+### 4.5 Membership
+
+Membership is a specialized dated edge rather than repeated text fields.
+
+```yaml
+organization_id: org_acme
+person_id: person_alex
+role: Executive Assistant
+department: Leadership
+cost_center: IE-EXEC-01
+location_id: loc_dublin
+started_on: 2024-04-01
+ended_on: null
+primary: true
+source: directory_import
+```
+
+This permits historical filtering, multiple concurrent roles, and accurate organization graphs.
+
+### 4.6 Interaction
+
+An interaction can link multiple people, organizations, groups, resources, commitments, or events.
+
+Types include:
+
+- in-person;
+- call;
+- email;
+- message;
+- video meeting;
+- shared activity;
+- gift or card;
+- introduction;
+- social interaction;
+- comment or post interaction;
+- support provided or received;
+- other.
+
+The user decides which types count as “meaningful” for maintenance rules. A reaction or automated email does not automatically strengthen a relationship.
+
+### 4.7 Resource
+
+A Resource is a first-class reference that can be connected to any entity, relationship, interaction, note, commitment, or event.
+
+Resource types:
+
+- local file;
+- external URL;
+- photo;
+- document;
+- email message or thread reference;
+- calendar event or invitation;
+- contact card;
+- map/location;
+- audio note;
+- meeting recording reference;
+- bookmark;
+- gift idea/product reference;
+- attachment collection.
+
+Resource rules:
+
+- local files use content hashes and portable relative paths;
+- external URLs store canonical URL, title, source, added date, and optional user-approved metadata;
+- no remote URL is fetched without an explicit connection/egress permission;
+- calendar invitations retain source UID and may also store the original `.ics` file;
+- email bodies and attachments remain separate opt-in permissions;
+- every Resource has backlinks;
+- a deleted external resource does not delete the note or interaction that referenced it.
+
+---
+
+## 5. Topic Packs
+
+Topic Packs solve the problem that different people require different information without turning every profile into an enormous form.
+
+A pack can be:
+
+- enabled for the whole workspace;
+- included in a profile template;
+- required for a group or organization;
+- activated for one person;
+- supplied by a plugin;
+- hidden for a role;
+- versioned and exported.
+
+### 5.1 Built-in packs
+
+#### Identity and communication
+
+- pronunciation;
+- preferred name;
+- pronouns;
+- language;
+- time zone;
+- preferred